<p>You ask a happy customer to leave a review. They do. You see the notification pop up, feel good about it, and move on. Two weeks later, that review is gone. No notice. No explanation. Just gone.</p>

<p>This is happening to businesses across the country at a scale that nobody expected. Google review deletions surged by more than 600% between January and July of 2025. At peak levels, nearly 1,200 monitored business locations saw at least one review removed in a single week.</p>

<p>The problem is not just that fake reviews are being removed. Legitimate, honest reviews from real customers are disappearing too.</p>

<h2>Five-Star Reviews Are Getting Hit the Hardest</h2>

<p>This is the part that stings. Five-star reviews account for approximately 38% of all deleted reviews. One-star reviews make up about 31%. The reviews in the middle, the three and four-star ratings, are far less likely to be removed.</p>

<p>Google's AI moderation system is designed to catch fake reviews, and it has gotten aggressive. But aggressive moderation means more false positives. The system views enthusiastic praise with suspicion because fake positive reviews tend to use similar language patterns. The result is that genuine five-star reviews from real customers are getting caught in the filter.</p>

<p>Home services is one of the hardest-hit categories. Businesses in this space show a strong skew toward five-star review deletions, with far fewer removals in the middle of the rating scale.</p>

<h2>Why Reviews Are Disappearing</h2>

<p>Google's Gemini AI system now analyzes reviews using pattern detection that evaluates reviewer account history, review content, timing patterns, and the relationship between the reviewer and the business. If any of those signals look off, the review gets flagged.</p>

<p>Here is what can trigger a deletion even when the review is real. A customer who has never left a Google review before writes a glowing five-star review. The system flags it because the account has no history. A customer who left multiple reviews for businesses in the same category within a short window gets flagged for suspicious behavior. A customer who used ChatGPT or another AI tool to help them write their review violates Google's policy, even if the experience was genuine and the sentiment is their own. Google now explicitly prohibits AI-generated review content regardless of authenticity.</p>

<p>Most customers have no idea these rules exist. They are just trying to help your business.</p>

<h2>What Business Owners Are Seeing</h2>

<p>The reports from business owners are consistent. Reviews disappearing overnight with no notification. Reviews stuck in "pending" status that never publish. Customers saying they left a review that is nowhere to be found. Entire batches of reviews from a specific time period being quietly removed. Older reviews that had been live for months or years suddenly vanishing.</p>

<p>Industry data suggests that between 5 and 15 percent of reviews may eventually be removed across all businesses, but some businesses see much higher rates, especially those in high-scrutiny categories like home services.</p>

<h2>How to Protect Your Review Profile</h2>

<p><strong>Generate reviews consistently, not in bursts.</strong> A steady flow of two to three new reviews per week looks natural to Google's algorithm. Twenty reviews in a single week looks suspicious, even if every one of them is real. Spread your requests out.</p>

<p><strong>Diversify how customers leave reviews.</strong> Do not send every customer the same link at the same time from the same email template. Vary your approach: text messages after some jobs, a card with a QR code after others, a verbal ask during the final walkthrough. Different patterns reduce the chance of triggering bulk-detection algorithms.</p>

<p><strong>Respond to every review.</strong> Google's algorithm now weights owner response rate as a quality signal. A profile where the owner responds to every review looks more active and legitimate than one where reviews go unanswered. After a March 2026 update, review recency and response rate carry more weight than total review count.</p>

<p><strong>Monitor your review count weekly.</strong> Keep a simple log of your total review count and average rating. If the number drops, you will know immediately rather than discovering it months later.</p>

<p><strong>Do not ask customers to use AI to write their reviews.</strong> If a customer asks you what to say, give them simple guidance: mention the specific service you performed, the city, and what made the experience good. A short, specific, human-written review is more valuable and more durable than a polished AI-generated paragraph.</p>

<h2>The Bigger Picture</h2>

<p>Google is fighting a real problem. Fake reviews are a genuine threat to every local business. But the current approach is catching real reviews in the crossfire, and there is no easy appeals process when it happens.</p>

<p>The only reliable defense is volume and consistency. Keep generating real reviews from real customers, keep responding, and keep monitoring. The businesses that treat their review profile as an ongoing priority will weather this better than those who set it and forget it.</p>
